This I don't like.” Whatever we like makes us happy — happy because of our delusion: happy because of our delusion, not happy because it's right.
When the mind is quiet, the Buddha tells us not to be intoxicated by it.
When it's distracted, he tells us not to be intoxicated by it.
Things happen in all kinds of ways.
There's addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division.
That's how we can calculate numbers, but we want there to be just multiplication so that we can have lots of everything.
We want to do away with addition, do away with subtraction, do away with division — and our calculations will all be stupid.
If we had nothing but multiplication, would we have any space to put everything?
If that's how we think, we'll stay in a turmoil.
The Buddha said that that sort of thinking has no discernment.
Stillness of mind — tranquility — comes from being far away from preoccupations.
If you don't hear much of anything, the mind settles down and is still.
To get this kind of stillness, you have to go off into seclusion, to a place that's quiet and still.
If you can get away from your preoccupations, not seeing this, not knowing about that, the mind can settle down.
But that's like a disease, a disease like cancer.
There's a swelling but it doesn't yet hurt.
